anings":["English and Scottish: from the vernacular pronunciation in Middle English and Older Scots of the personal name   Michael  . See   Michelson  .","English and Scottish: nickname for a big man, from Middle English <i>michel</i>, <i>mechel</i>, <i>muchel</i> ‘big’.","Irish (County Connacht): surname adopted as equivalent of   Mulvihill  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Michell","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Etienne, Yvrose.","English (Cornwall): variant of   Mitchell   and   Michel  .","German: variant of   Michel  . This surname is rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Mutch","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeenshire) and English (Lancashire and Cheshire): nickname for a large (tall or fat) person, from Middle English <i>moche</i>, <i>muche</i> ‘big’ (a shortened form of <i>mochel</i>, <i>muchel</i>). Compare   Mitchell  ,   Meikle  , and   Muckle  ."]},{"name":"Meikle","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Middle Scots <i>mekill</i>, <i>meikill</i> ‘big’. Compare   Mitchell   2,   Muckle  , and   Mutch  ."]},{"name":"Mickle","meanings":["English (Northumberland): nickname from Middle English <i>mikel</i>, <i>mekel</i>, <i>mukel</i> ‘big’. Compare   Mitchell  ,   Meikle  , and   Mutch  .","Americanized form of German   Mickel   1 or of a homonymous Germanized Sorbian surname (see   Mickel   2)."]},{"name":"Michael","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Jewish, and Greek: from the personal name <i>Michael</i>, ultimately from Hebrew <i>Mika’el</i> ‘Who is like God?’. This was borne by an archangel in the Bible, the protector of Israel (Daniel 10:13, 12:1; Rev. 12:7). In Christian tradition, Michael was regarded as the warrior archangel, conqueror of Satan, and the personal name was correspondingly popular throughout Europe, especially in knightly and military families. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian <b>Mihály</b> (see   Mihaly  ), Czech and Slovak   Michal  , Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Mikhael   and   Mikhail  , and also patronymics and other derivatives from these names, e.g. Greek   Papamichael  , its cognate <b>Papamichalis</b>, and   Michaelides  , Serbian <b>Mihajlović</b> (see   Mihajlovic  ), and Slovenian <b>Mihelčič</b> (see   Mihelcic  ). Compare   Mikeal  ."]},{"name":"Mitchel","meanings":["English: variant of   Mitchell  ."]},{"name":"Mixell","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Mitchell  ."]},{"name":"Muckle","meanings":["English (Northumberland): nickname for a big man, from Middle English <i>mikel</i>, <i>mekel</i>, <i>mukel</i> ‘big’ (Old English <i>mycel</i>). Compare   Mitchell  ,   Meikle   and   Mutch  .","South German: from a diminutive of   Muck   ‘gnat’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":0,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":9,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":54,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - W